{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503871"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2091"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.81,0,0.01,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31534"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2091"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"243"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34779"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35284"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31534"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to her general practice to discuss the results of a cervical screening test performed the previous week. The results of the test showed that genotypes 16/18 were detected, and other genotypes (not 16/18) were not. Reflex liquid based cytology (LBC) reported high grade dysplasia (HSIL).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent referral to gynaecological oncology","Referral to gynaecology for colposcopy","Reassure and return to routine screening","Ask the patient to return to collect a new sample in 6-12 weeks","Repeat the HPV test in 12 months"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECervical cancer screening in Australia is offered to women aged 25-74 as a 5-yearly Human Papilloma Virus (HPV) test. The HPV test replaced the Pap Smear in 2017, and detects the presence of HPV with partial genotyping. When HPV is detected, \u0026nbsp;reflex liquid based cytology (LBC) is performed. If the LBC shows moderate to severe dysplastic changes (HSIL) or if the oncogenic strains of HPV, 16/18 are detected, then referral to gynaecologist for colposcopy is indicated. If HPV other types/non-16/18 is detected or LBC is reported as mild dysplasia (LSIL), then the HPV test should be repeated in 12 months at which point if HPV is still present then colposcopy is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s cervical screening test has detected HSIL in the presence of HPV 16/18, and thus she needs a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral to a gynaecologist\u003C/strong\u003E for colposcopy. Most clinics would triage this referral so that the patient would be reviewed within 4 weeks. An urgent referral to the gynaecology oncology team is not necessary immediately but would be undertaken if cancer cells are detected on LBC, biopsy or LLETZ following colposcopy. Reassuring and returning to routine screening is incorrect as is recollecting the sample in 6-12 weeks. It is unlikely that there would be any difference in the sample if retaken at this time point as HPV can take 12 months or more to be cleared. Repeating the test in 12 months is not in keeping with the current guidelines for HSIL and HPV 16/18.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["High grade dysplasia on a cervical screening test is an indication for colposcopy."],"references":["Department of Health. National Cancer Screening Program Canberra Australian Government; 2020 [updated 23 September 2020. Available from: http://www.cancerscreening.gov.au/internet/screening/publishing.nsf/Content/healthcare-providers. Accessed 1/10/2020.","Khieu M, Butler SL. High Grade Squamous Intraepithelial Lesion (HSIL).  StatPearls. Treasure Island (FL)2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-12T10:43:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-07T11:40:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2091"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31534"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"m